      "content": "I apologize for the confusion; I can certainly stop using the goblin metaphors and focus strictly on the mechanical and electrical reasons for your AC unit's behavior.\n\nIf the fan is humming but not spinning, the most common causes are indeed electrical or mechanical failures. A **failed start capacitor** is the primary suspect; this component stores energy to help the motor start, and if it shorts out, it can cause the motor to hum loudly without turning. Another possibility is a **seized motor bearing**, where friction has built up enough to lock the rotor in place, or **debris** (like a leaf or piece of insulation) caught in the fan blades, physically blocking rotation.\n\nRegarding safety, you are absolutely correct to cut the power at the breaker before inspecting the unit. Even with the power off, capacitors can hold a dangerous charge, and the motor could potentially start if the circuit is reconnected improperly. If you are not comfortable diagnosing these components, it is best to contact a licensed HVAC technician.",
